## Part 3: Navigation & Architecture Issues

### NAV-01 — Sidebar Has Too Many Items (16+ nav items)
The sidebar currently shows 16+ navigation items in a scrollable list. This violates the "5-second rule" — users can't quickly orient themselves.

**Recommended restructure:**
```
📊  Dashboard
──── INVENTORY ────
📦  Products
🚚  Suppliers
🏭  Warehouses
──── OPERATIONS ────
📈  Demand & Forecasts
🛒  Replenishment
📋  Purchase Orders
──── MANUFACTURING ────
🧱  Raw Materials
📝  Bill of Materials
🏗️  Manufacturers
⭐  Recommendations
🔧  Production Orders
──── FINANCE (Owner only) ────
💰  Cash Flow
📊  Financial Analytics
──── SYSTEM ────
🔗  Integrations
⚙️  Settings
```

With dividers and section headings, this becomes scannable at a glance.

### NAV-02 — Top Bar Title Is Hardcoded and Incomplete
The [_TopBar](file:///c:/Users/akara/Development/projects/ma5zony/lib/widgets/main_layout.dart#330-377) uses a series of `if/else` string checks to set the page title. It misses many routes (Raw Materials, BOM, Manufacturers, etc.). Use GoRouter's current route name directly.

### NAV-03 — No Breadcrumbs for Sub-Pages
Pages like Order Detail (`/orders/:id`) and Production Order Detail (`/production-orders/:id`) have no breadcrumb navigation. Users can't tell where they are or navigate back without using the browser.

### NAV-04 — No Mobile / Tablet Responsive Layout
The sidebar at `width < 800px` collapses to just icons (72px wide) with no labels, and there's no hamburger menu. On tablets this makes the app nearly unusable. Add a proper drawer-based mobile nav.

### NAV-05 — No Onboarding / First-Run Experience
A new user who signs up sees a dashboard full of zeros and empty screens with no guidance. Add a first-run checklist widget (e.g., "Get started in 4 steps"):
1. ✅ Connected Shopify
2. ☐ Import your products (link → Products)
3. ☐ Add your suppliers (link → Suppliers)
4. ☐ Run your first forecast (link → Forecasts)

---

## Part 4: End-to-End User Journeys (Missing Core Workflows)

A production-grade supply chain system needs to support connected, cohesive workflows rather than just siloed data management screens. The current UI lacks the connective tissue between related actions.

### JOURNEY-01 — The "Procure-to-Pay" (P2P) Gap
**Current State:** Replenishment triggers a 'Purchase Order'.
**The Missing Links:** 
- **Goods Receipt Notes (GRN):** Once an order is placed, how does the stock actually arrive? There is no screen to "Receive Goods", verify quantities against the PO, and update the actual stock levels in warehouses.
- **Supplier Bills & Payment:** The Cash Flow screen won't work correctly without tracking when supplier bills are due (AP - Accounts Payable) and resolving them against Purchase Orders.

### JOURNEY-02 — The "Order-to-Cash" (O2C) Gap
**Current State:** Demand data drops in from Shopify (B2C), but there is no native B2B outbound workflow.
**The Missing Links:**
- **Sales Orders Module:** A screen to create outbound Wholesale/B2B manual sales orders.
- **Fulfillment Pipeline:** A "Pick & Pack" screen for warehouse workers to fulfill Shopify & B2B orders.
- **Invoicing & Accounts Receivable:** Tracking payments owed by wholesale clients, which is critical for accurate cash flow projections.

### JOURNEY-03 — The "Plan-to-Produce" Gap
**Current State:** BOM → Recommendation → Production Order.
**The Missing Links:**
- **Component Allocation:** When a Production Order is created, the raw materials must be "Allocated" or "Reserved" so they aren't accidentally used elsewhere.
- **Work in Progress (WIP):** Moving a Production Order from "Draft" → "In Production" → "Completed", at which point it automatically deducts Raw Materials and adds Finished Goods to stock.

---

## Part 5: Frontend Architectural Overhaul (Codebase UX)

Drawing on robust frontend architecture skills and patterns, the following changes will dramatically improve developer UX and long-term UI stability.

### ARCH-01 — Refactor AppState (God Object) to MVVM
Currently, the UI is heavily coupled to a monolithic `AppState` provider.
- **Recommendation:** Implement the **Model-View-ViewModel (MVVM)** pattern or standard Flux structure. Break `AppState` into distinct domain stores (e.g., `ProductViewModel`, `OrderViewModel`, `ForecastViewModel`). This enables granular state loading, separation of concerns, and prevents unnecessary widget rebuilds.

### ARCH-02 — Adopt Presentational vs. Container Components 
Many UI screens fetch data and render complex widgets in the same file.
- **Recommendation:** Separate screens into pure "Presentational" dumb widgets (e.g., `ProductTable`) and "Container" logic widgets (e.g., `ProductsView` that watches the ViewModel). This improves testability and reusability of UI components and reduces visual spaghetti code.

### ARCH-03 — Optimized Loading via Progressive Disclosure
- **Recommendation:** The current UI blocks the entire screen with a spinner on load. Implement skeleton loading screens (especially for the Dashboard) and lazy-load heavier analytical charts below the fold to achieve a sub-1-second "Time to Interactive" experience.

---

## Part 6: Backend Improvements

### BE-01 — No Request Validation on API Routes
The backend routes ([products.ts](file:///c:/Users/akara/Development/projects/ma5zony_backend/src/routes/products.ts), [suppliers.ts](file:///c:/Users/akara/Development/projects/ma5zony_backend/src/routes/suppliers.ts), etc.) do not validate request bodies. Any malformed payload goes straight to Firestore.

**Fix:** Add a validation middleware using `zod` or manual checks:
```typescript
// Example: POST /api/products
if (!req.body.name || !req.body.sku) {
  return res.status(400).json({ error: 'name and sku are required' });
}
```

### BE-02 — Forecast Endpoint Doesn't Handle Insufficient Data
When fewer than `smaWindow` demand periods exist, the SMA calculation will produce `NaN` or throw. The endpoint should return a `422 Unprocessable Entity` with a clear message: *"Insufficient demand data: need at least 3 months of records."*

### BE-03 — No Rate Limiting
The backend API has no rate limiting. Any authenticated user could hammer the forecast endpoint repeatedly. Add `express-rate-limit`.

### BE-04 — Shopify Sync Doesn't Write Demand Records Correctly
Shopify order imports should write demand records to Firestore's `demand` collection. Based on the live data, this either isn't writing or is writing to the wrong collection/document structure. Audit the `importShopifyOrders` service and its Firestore write path.

### BE-05 — No Pagination on API Endpoints
All list endpoints (`/api/products`, `/api/demand`, etc.) return all records. With growing data, this will cause performance issues. Add cursor-based pagination using Firestore's `.startAfter()`.

### BE-06 — No Firestore Indexes Defined
Complex queries (demand records filtered by productId + date range) will fail without composite Firestore indexes. Define required indexes in `firestore.indexes.json`.

### BE-07 — CORS is Open (`app.use(cors())`)
The backend accepts requests from any origin. Restrict to your frontend domain:
```typescript
app.use(cors({ origin: ['https://your-app.web.app', 'http://localhost:8888'] }));
```

### BE-08 — No Health Monitoring
Add a `/api/health` endpoint that returns: server uptime, Firebase connection status, and last Shopify sync timestamp. This enables monitoring and alerting in production.

---

## Part 7: New Features & Suggested Additions

### FEAT-01 — 📱 Onboarding Wizard
A guided 4-step setup flow after first login:
1. Company profile (name, currency, fiscal year start)
2. Connect Shopify or manually add first products
3. Add suppliers
4. Run first forecast

### FEAT-02 — 🔔 Push/Email Notifications
Currently, notifications exist in-app (bell icon). Extend to:
- Email alerts for critical stock events
- Daily/weekly digest report to owner
- Slack/Teams webhook for production order status changes

### FEAT-03 — 📊 Dashboard Customization
Allow users to pin/unpin KPI cards, rearrange dashboard sections, and choose which charts appear. Save preferences to Firestore per user.

### FEAT-04 — 📥 CSV/Excel Import for Products & Demand
Not everyone has Shopify. Allow CSV upload for:
- Products (bulk add with field mapping tool)
- Historical demand data (date, product SKU, quantity)
- Suppliers (name, email, lead time)

### FEAT-05 — 🔍 Advanced Search & Filters
Upgrade the global search to support:
- Cross-entity search (products, suppliers, orders, raw materials)
- Keyboard shortcut (`⌘K` / `Ctrl+K`) to open search
- Filter by status, category, date range within search results

### FEAT-06 — 📈 Analytics Export (PDF/CSV)
Every analytics page (Financial Analytics, Forecasts, Replenishment) should have a "Download Report" button generating a formatted PDF or CSV for month-end reports and stakeholder presentations.

### FEAT-07 — 🌍 Multi-Currency Support
For businesses that source internationally, allow products/suppliers to have different currencies, with an exchange rate setting for financial calculations.

### FEAT-08 — 🗺️ Warehouse Map View
Visual map showing warehouse locations and their stock levels, useful for multi-location businesses.

### FEAT-09 — 🔄 Automated Replenishment Triggers
Allow owners to configure automatic purchase order creation when stock falls below ROP, without manual approval for trusted suppliers.

### FEAT-10 — 📋 Audit Trail / Activity Log
Record every data change: who added/edited/deleted a product, supplier, or order, and when. Essential for production B2B environments.

